<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="Publisher" Owner="NLM"><PMID Version="1">41773874</PMID><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>03</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1937-1578</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><PubDate><Year>2025</Year><Month>Aug</Month><Day>04</Day></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Retinal cases &amp; brief reports</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Retin Cases Brief Rep</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>A 3-year-old pediatric case of torpedo maculopathy associated with a serous retinal detachment.</ArticleTitle><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1097/ICB.0000000000001795</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="PURPOSE" NlmCategory="OBJECTIVE">To report an atypical retinal finding of torpedo maculopathy in a three-year-old boy.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="METHOD" NlmCategory="METHODS">A retrospective case report.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="RESULTS" NlmCategory="RESULTS">Optical Coherence Tomography examination of the retinal lesion showed a hyper-reflectivity of the outer layers associated with a Serous Retinal Detachment (SRD) with an extension of the outer segments of the photoreceptors. Furthermore, the external limiting membrane and the retinal pigment epithelium are intact. Although the reflectance of the ellipsoid zone appears diminished, no disruptions were observed, suggesting that the ellipsoid zone is likely undamaged.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CONCLUSION" NlmCategory="CONCLUSIONS">This maculopathy is predominantly associated with a SRD, rather than the tissue atrophy typically described in types 1, 2, 3, and 4. This association has already been described but is not included in current classifications. We propose to potentially add a"with SRF" stage to the current classifications.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>Copyright &#xa9; 2025 The Author(s). Published by Wolters Kluwer Health, Inc. on behalf of the Opthalmic Communications Society, Inc.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Elodie</LastName><ForeName>Viinikka</ForeName><Initials>V</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Ophthalmology, Nouvel H&#xf4;pital Civil, University of Strasbourg, France.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Tristan</LastName><ForeName>Bourcier</ForeName><Initials>B</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>David</LastName><ForeName>Gaucher</ForeName><Initials>G</Initials></Author></AuthorList><Language>eng</Language><PublicationTypeList><PublicationType UI="D016428">Journal Article</PublicationType></PublicationTypeList><ArticleDate DateType="Electronic"><Year>2025</Year><Month>08</Month><Day>04</Day></ArticleDate></Article><MedlineJournalInfo><Country>United States</Country><MedlineTA>Retin Cases Brief Rep</MedlineTA><NlmUniqueID>101298744</NlmUniqueID><ISSNLinking>1935-1089</ISSNLinking></MedlineJournalInfo><CitationSubset>IM</CitationSubset><KeywordList Owner="NOTNLM"><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">cavitation</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">congenital</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">lesion</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">retina</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">serous retinal detachment</Keyword><Keyword MajorTopicYN="N">torpedo maculopathy</Keyword></KeywordList></MedlineCitation><PubmedData><History><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="medline"><Year>2026</Year><Month>3</Month><Day>3</Day><Hour>12</Hour><Minute>32</Minute></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="pubmed"><Year>2026</Year><Month>3</Month><Day>3</Day><Hour>12</Hour><Minute>32</Minute></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="entrez"><Year>2026</Year><Month>3</Month><Day>3</Day><Hour>9</Hour><Minute>3</Minute></PubMedPubDate></History><PublicationStatus>aheadofprint</PublicationStatus><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">41773874</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="doi">10.1097/ICB.0000000000001795</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pii">01